## Diagnosis

The `micro` rendering mode was introduced to "do something" with tiles in the 32-64px width range, but 8px text is unreadable by any standard. The component is trying to render a label where it physically cannot fit, which is worse than rendering nothing.

## Root Cause

**AP-072 (Graceful Degradation vs. Harmful Degradation)** — the component degrades to a harmful state (unreadable 8px text) rather than gracefully omitting content that cannot fit. Shrinking text below a legibility floor to accommodate a constraint is never the right trade-off; the correct response is to hide the label entirely and let the tile communicate through colour/tooltip alone.

---

## Fix

### 1. Remove the `micro` mode entirely from the size-threshold logic

Wherever the tile size bands are defined (likely something like `getTileRenderMode`, a size enum, or inline ternaries in the JSX):

**`src/components/KnowledgeTreemap/KnowledgeTreemap.tsx`** (or `.jsx`)

```tsx
// BEFORE — three bands, micro is harmful
type TileRenderMode = 'full' | 'compact' | 'micro';

function getTileRenderMode(width: number, height: number): TileRenderMode {
  const area = width * height;
  if (area >= 4096) return 'full';       // ≥ 64×64
  if (area >= 1024) return 'compact';    // ≥ 32×32
  return 'micro';                        // anything smaller — BAD
}
```

```tsx
// AFTER — two bands, small tiles are label-less
type TileRenderMode = 'full' | 'compact' | 'hidden';

const LABEL_MIN_WIDTH  = 48;  // px — narrower than this, hide the label
const LABEL_MIN_HEIGHT = 32;  // px — shorter than this, hide the label

function getTileRenderMode(width: number, height: number): TileRenderMode {
  if (width >= LABEL_MIN_WIDTH && height >= LABEL_MIN_HEIGHT) {
    // enough room for at least the compact label
    return width >= 80 && height >= 56 ? 'full' : 'compact';
  }
  return 'hidden'; // tile too small — show colour + tooltip only
}
```

### 2. Remove micro-specific font styles from the tile renderer

```tsx
// BEFORE
const labelStyles: Record<TileRenderMode, string> = {
  full:    'text-sm font-medium leading-tight',
  compact: 'text-xs font-medium leading-none',
  micro:   'text-[8px] font-medium leading-none',   // ← delete
};

// AFTER
const labelStyles: Record<TileRenderMode, string> = {
  full:    'text-sm font-medium leading-tight',
  compact: 'text-xs font-medium leading-none',
  hidden:  '',   // no label rendered at all
};
```

### 3. Update the tile JSX to gate on `hidden`

```tsx
// BEFORE
<div className={labelStyles[mode]}>{category.name}</div>

// AFTER
{mode !== 'hidden' && (
  <span className={labelStyles[mode]} aria-hidden="true">
    {category.name}
  </span>
)}
```

### 4. Ensure every tile has a tooltip regardless of mode

Small tiles must still be discoverable — a tooltip (or `title` attribute as a baseline) carries the name when the label is hidden:

```tsx
<div
  role="img"
  aria-label={category.name}          // screen-reader always gets the name
  title={category.name}               // native tooltip fallback
  data-tooltip={category.name}        // hook for your custom tooltip system
  className={cn(tileSizeClass, tileColorClass)}
>
  {mode !== 'hidden' && (
    <span className={labelStyles[mode]} aria-hidden="true">
      {category.name}
    </span>
  )}
</div>
```

### 5. Delete the `micro` Tailwind class if it was added to the design token layer

**`src/styles/typography.css`** or **`tailwind.config.ts`**:

```ts
// Remove any entry like:
fontSize: {
  micro: ['8px', { lineHeight: '10px' }],   // ← delete this
}
```

---

## Principle

> **A component must have a legibility floor, not a font-size floor.**
>
> When content cannot fit at a minimum readable size (≥ 11px body, ≥ 10px caption — the Elan baseline), the correct response is to **omit the content**, not to shrink it further. Visibility and readability are not the same thing. A label rendered at 8px is worse than no label: it creates visual noise, fails accessibility contrast-ratio requirements (WCAG 1.4.4 Resize Text), and implies meaning the user cannot actually read.
>
> **Rule:** define a minimum legible size for each text role. Below the threshold that can contain it, hide the text and substitute a tooltip/aria-label. Never introduce a new font-size tier just to squeeze text into an undersized container.

This prevents the pattern from creeping back: any future "let's just make it smaller" PR has a named principle and explicit px thresholds to argue against.
